    <etym xml:lang="ru">Восходит к *%ibarza%i-, <mentioned xml:lang="ine"
            ><lang/><w>*bhrəgo-</w></mentioned>: <mentioned xml:lang="tg"
            ><lang/><w>burz</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="tg"><w>burs</w><gloss><q>арча
                    (дерево)</q></gloss></mentioned>, , <mentioned xml:lang="wbl"
                    ><lang/><w>furz</w><gloss><q>береза</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned
            xml:lang="sgy"><lang/><w>bərež</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sgh"
                ><lang/><w>bəruj</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="sgh"
                    ><w>bərüž</w><gloss><q>береста</q></gloss></mentioned>, , <mentioned
            xml:lang="kho"><lang/><w>braṃja</w><gloss><q>береза</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref
                target="#ref_BSOS"/><biblScope>VIII 120</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned
            xml:lang="kho"><lang/><w>bruṃjə</w><gloss><q>береста</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref
                target="#ref_Leumann"/><biblScope>481</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned xml:lang="sa"
                ><lang/><w>bhūrja-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="cu"
            ><lang/><w>брѣза</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"
            ><lang/><w>береза</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="lt"
            ><lang/><w>bèržas</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="de"
                    ><lang/><w>Birke</w><gloss><q>береза</q></gloss></mentioned> и пр. Семантически
        связано с понятием „свет“, „сиять“ (<mentioned xml:lang="ae"
        ><lang/><w>brāz-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/><w>bhrāj-</w></mentioned>)
        → „светлое дерево= береза“. Из осетинского идет <mentioned xml:lang="krc-x-balkar"
                ><lang/><w>mərzə</w><gloss><q>береза</q></gloss></mentioned>. Кроме ‘березы’, к
        индоевропейскому слою языка относятся, по-видимому, названия ивы (<ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_xærīs"/>), ольхи (<ref type="xr" target="#entry_færv"/>), ильма (<ref
            type="xr" target="#entry_talm"/>). См. также <ref type="xr" target="#entry_tūlʒ"/>
        ‘дуб’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kærz"/> ‘ясень’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_tærs"/>
        ‘бук’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_næzy"/> ‘сосна’.%n<bibl><ref
                target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"/><biblScope>II 85, III 138</biblScope></bibl>;
                <bibl><ref target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."/><biblScope>14</biblScope></bibl>. —
                <bibl><ref target="#ref_Hübschmann._Oss."/><biblScope>28</biblScope></bibl>. —
                <bibl><ref target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>32, 48</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
    <etym xml:lang="en">It traces back to *%ibarza%i-, <mentioned xml:lang="ine"
                ><lang/><w>*bhrəgo-</w></mentioned>: <mentioned xml:lang="tg"
            ><lang/><w>burz</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="tg"
                ><w>burs</w><gloss><q>Juniper</q></gloss></mentioned>, , <mentioned xml:lang="wbl"
                ><lang/><w>furz</w><gloss><q>birch</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned
            xml:lang="sgy"><lang/><w>bərež</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sgh"
                ><lang/><w>bəruj</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="sgh"
                    ><w>bərüž</w><gloss><q>birchbark</q></gloss></mentioned>, , <mentioned
            xml:lang="kho"><lang/><w>braṃja</w><gloss><q>birch</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref
                target="#ref_BSOS"/><biblScope>VIII 120</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned
            xml:lang="kho"><lang/><w>bruṃjə</w><gloss><q>birchbark</q></gloss></mentioned>
                (<bibl><ref target="#ref_Leumann"/><biblScope>481</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned
            xml:lang="sa"><lang/><w>bhūrja-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="cu"
                ><lang/><w>brěza</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"
            ><lang/><w>bereza</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="lt"
            ><lang/><w>bèržas</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="de"
                    ><lang/><w>Birke</w><gloss><q>birch</q></gloss></mentioned> etc. It is
        semantically connected with the notion ‘light’, ‘shine’ (<mentioned xml:lang="ae"
                ><lang/><w>brāz-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"
            ><lang/><w>bhrāj-</w></mentioned>) → “light tree” = ‘birch’. The word <mentioned
            xml:lang="krc-x-balkar"><lang/><w>mərzə</w><gloss><q>береза</q></gloss></mentioned>
        comes from Ossetic. Apart from ‘birch’, the following notions relate to the Indo-European
        part of the language: willow (<ref type="xr" target="#entry_xærīs"/>), alder-tree (<ref
            type="xr" target="#entry_færv"/>), elm (<ref type="xr" target="#entry_talm"/>). See also
            <ref type="xr" target="#entry_tūlʒ"/> ‘oak’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kærz"/>
        ‘ash-tree’, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_tærs"/> ‘beech’, <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_næzy"/> ‘pine-tree’.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"
                /><biblScope>II 85, III 138</biblScope></bibl>; <bibl><ref
                target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."/><biblScope>14</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref
                target="#ref_Hübschmann._Oss."/><biblScope>28</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref
                target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>32, 48</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
</entry>
